#Text=Fanny Wilson ( U.S. Civil War )
#Text=Not to be confused with Fanny Wilson .
#Text=Fanny ( Fannie ) Wilson , disguised as a man , enlisted as a soldier in the Union Army during the U.S. Civil War with her close friend Nellie Graves .
#Text=At the time , women were not allowed to serve in the Union Army so Wilson and Graves had to masquerade as men .
#Text=Pre-Civil War
#Text=Born in Long Island , New York , Wilson fell in love with and became engaged to a man before taking a trip to Lafayette , Indiana to visit some relatives in 1860 .
#Text=Her friend , Graves , accompanied her on this trip .
#Text=Both were deeply in love with men they had left back home . [ 1 ]
#Text=In early 1861 , as America moved closer to Civil War Wilson and Graves returned home to Long Island .
#Text=During the trip home , they thought of a plan to stay close to their lovers if war should occur , since both men had stated they would join the Union Army should war break out .
#Text=They intended to enlist in the same regiment as their men , but in different companies .
#Text=This would lessen their risk of discovery , while still being close to their lovers . [ 1 ]
#Text=Civil War
#Text=In 1862 , the two men enlisted in the new regiment being formed at Camp Cadwallader , in Beverly , New Jersey .
#Text=The 24th New Jersey Infantry Regiment was mustered into Federal service on September 16 , 1862 .
#Text=Wilson and Graves enacted their plan .
#Text=They cut their hair and put on men 's clothing .
#Text=Graves had a more difficult time concealing her sex than Wilson did .
#Text=Wilson was described as having a " ... masculine voice " and as " tanned and smart and somewhat educated . " [ 2 ]
#Text=She was nineteen at the time .
#Text=Their plan worked , they marched and trained alongside their lovers without being discovered .
#Text=They served in the defense of Washington D.C. until December 1862 when the regiment was sent to Fredericksburg , Virginia , where they participated in the Battle of Fredericksburg .
#Text=After seeing the horrors of war firsthand , both women viewed their service in a more serious light .
#Text=They were determined to continue serving , not because of their lovers , but because they felt a need to serve their country . [ 1 ]
#Text=In early May 1863 , the regiment fought in the Battle of Chancellorsville .
#Text=During the battle , Wilson 's lover was seriously wounded .
#Text=After the battle , Wilson took care and watched over him , nearly revealing herself .
#Text=Despite Wilson 's effort , her lover died .
#Text=At some point during this time , Graves ' lover was also killed , however it is unknown when or where he died . [ 3 ]
#Text=Soon after their lovers ' deaths , Wilson and Graves contracted an ' unspecified ' illness . [ 2 ]
#Text=Both were sent to an army hospital in Cairo , Illinois .
#Text=While there Wilson and Graves ' true sex was discovered .
#Text=Graves recovered first and was discharged , parting ways with Wilson .
#Text=After Wilson was discharged she became a ballet dancer with the Cairo Theater .
#Text=After two performances she quit and looked for another regiment to join , feeling the need to serve her country .
#Text=She joined the 3rd Illinois Cavalry as they were on their way to Vicksburg , Mississippi .
#Text=During the second assault on Vicksburg on May 22 Wilson was wounded in battle , though not seriously .
#Text=She was treated without her true sex being discovered .
#Text=She fully recovered and continued on with the regiment . [ 1 ]
#Text=On August 5 , 1863 , Wilson was riding through Memphis , Tennessee with a fellow soldier when a guard stopped them .
#Text=She was arrested on suspicion of being a woman in men 's clothing and being a spy .
#Text=While being questioned , she proved she was a Union soldier .
#Text=Soon after , the authorities discharged her with female clothing and made her promise she would not disguise herself as a man again .
#Text=Fanny died on September 15 , 1864 of disease .
#Text=She is buried in the Memphis Tennessee National Cemetery , grave 621 ( reference : US National Cemetery Interment Control Forms ) .
#Text=Works cited
#Text=Blanton , DeAnne ( 2002 ) .
#Text=They fought like demons : women soldiers in the American Civil War .
#Text=Baton Rouge : Louisiana State University Press .
#Text=OCLC 315917223 .
